// ch05 §5.11: "A concept is optional, not mandatory, on a constrained
// parameter. Writing bare auto (no concept name in front of it) is
// legal -- it means the parameter's type is treated as fully opaque:
// the body may move it, store it, pass it to another function accepting
// a compatible (bare-or-narrower) parameter, and return it." This is
// explicitly documented as supported, but currently rejected ("expected
// a type name") -- confirmed not specific to lambdas either (see
// 18_closures/generic_lambda_with_auto_parameter.scpp, the same gap for
// a lambda's own bare auto parameter). Only the full-header-form bare
// type parameter (see full_header_form_with_bare_type_parameter.scpp)
// currently works.
int identity(auto x) {
    return x;
}

int main() {
    return identity(42);
}
